Title: Browser Client Process Memory Tampered
Description: If Browser Client is given access to memory, such as shared memory or pointers, or is given the ability to control what Web Application executes (for example, passing back a function pointer.), then Browser Client can tamper with Web Application. Consider if the function could work with less access to memory, such as passing data rather than pointers. Copy in data provided, and then validate it.

Title: Cross Site Scripting
Description: The web server 'Web Application' could be a subject to a cross-site scripting attack because it does not sanitize untrusted input.

Title: Elevation Using Impersonation
Description: Web Application may be able to impersonate the context of Browser Client in order to gain additional privilege.

Title: Elevation Using Impersonation
Description: Browser Client may be able to impersonate the context of Voter in order to gain additional privilege.

Title: Spoofing the Voter External Entity
Description: Voter may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to Browser Client. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.

Title: Spoofing of Destination Data Store Cookies
Description: Cookies may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Cookies. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.

Title: Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Web Application or Cookies
Description: Does Web Application or Cookies take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.

Title: Spoofing of Destination Data Store SQL Database
Description: SQL Database may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of SQL Database. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.

Title: Spoofing of Source Data Store Cookies
Description: Cookies may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to incorrect data delivered to SQL Database. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the source data store.

Title: Cross Site Scripting
Description: The web server 'Web Application' could be a subject to a cross-site scripting attack because it does not sanitize untrusted input.

Title: Spoofing of Source Data Store SQL Database
Description: SQL Database may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to incorrect data delivered to Web Application. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the source data store.

Title: Persistent Cross Site Scripting
Description: The web server 'Web Application' could be a subject to a persistent cross-site scripting attack because it does not sanitize data store 'SQL Database' inputs and output.

Title: Weak Access Control for a Resource
Description: Improper data protection of SQL Database can allow an attacker to read information not intended for disclosure. Review authorization settings.

Title: Spoofing the Web Application Process
Description: Web Application may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to Blockchain. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the source process.

Title: Spoofing of Destination Data Store Blockchain
Description: Blockchain may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Blockchain. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.

Title: The Blockchain Data Store Could Be Corrupted
Description: Data flowing across Generic Data Flow may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to corruption of Blockchain. Ensure the integrity of the data flow to the data store.

Title: Data Store Denies Blockchain Potentially Writing Data
Description: Blockchain claims that it did not write data received from an entity on the other side of the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.

Title: Data Flow Sniffing
Description: Data flowing across Generic Data Flow may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. Consider encrypting the data flow.

Title: Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Web Application or Blockchain
Description: Does Web Application or Blockchain take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.

Title: Data Flow Generic Data Flow Is Potentially Interrupted
Description: An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.

Title: Data Store Inaccessible
Description: An external agent prevents access to a data store on the other side of the trust boundary.

Title: Spoofing of Source Data Store Blockchain
Description: Blockchain may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to incorrect data delivered to Web Application. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the source data store.

Title: Cross Site Scripting
Description: The web server 'Web Application' could be a subject to a cross-site scripting attack because it does not sanitize untrusted input.

Title: Persistent Cross Site Scripting
Description: The web server 'Web Application' could be a subject to a persistent cross-site scripting attack because it does not sanitize data store 'Blockchain' inputs and output.

Title: Weak Access Control for a Resource
Description: Improper data protection of Blockchain can allow an attacker to read information not intended for disclosure. Review authorization settings.

Title: Spoofing the Web Application Process
Description: Web Application may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to information disclosure by Blockchain. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination process.

Title: Potential Data Repudiation by Web Application
Description: Web Application claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.

Title: Potential Process Crash or Stop for Web Application
Description: Web Application crashes, halts, stops or runs slowly; in all cases violating an availability metric.

Title: Data Flow Generic Data Flow Is Potentially Interrupted
Description: An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.

Title: Data Store Inaccessible
Description: An external agent prevents access to a data store on the other side of the trust boundary.

Title: Web Application May be Subject to Elevation of Privilege Using Remote Code Execution
Description: Blockchain may be able to remotely execute code for Web Application.

Title: Elevation by Changing the Execution Flow in Web Application
Description: An attacker may pass data into Web Application in order to change the flow of program execution within Web Application to the attacker's choosing.
